ed the same.", "author": "ethan@ethanhs.me", "id": 13191389, "time": "2018-04-09T09:23:36Z"}, {"text": "It'd be good to know what this is", "author": "milaninbugzilla@gmail.com", "id": 13196097, "time": "2018-04-10T20:53:08Z"}, {"text": "Can you still reproduce this?", "author": "jmuizelaar@mozilla.com", "id": 13216880, "time": "2018-04-18T21:50:39Z"}, {"text": "(In reply to Jeff Muizelaar [:jrmuizel] from comment #2)\n> Can you still reproduce this?\n\nYes, I can still repro this.", "author": "ethan@ethanhs.me", "id": 13217132, "time": "2018-04-18T23:38:18Z"}, {"text": "I can also reproduce this. It *mostly* looks like we're just dropping to greyscale, suggesting a fallback. However I see hints of colour as if subpixel was *kinda* still there? Might just be an artifact from how I'm zooming in windows though.", "author": "a.beingessner@gmail.com", "id": 13218828, "time": "2018-04-19T15:28:38Z"}, {"text": "At least for me, only reproduces with subpixel AA enabled, but not with it disabled. I tried running mozregression on this, and it claims bug 1339474, which turned on APZ for WR, is where this might have started. Kats, ideas?", "author": "lsalzman@mozilla.com", "id": 13225728, "time": "2018-04-23T01:53:09Z"}, {"text": "Sorry, I have no idea why turning on APZ would affect this. I can repro the behaviour on macOS with default WR-enabled settings as well as with layers.async-pan-zoom.enabled set to false. So I don't know if this is really specific to APZ or if that's just a red herring.", "author": "bugmail@mozilla.staktrace.com", "id": 13226535, "time": "2018-04-23T14:10:36Z"}, {"text": "This should be addressed by WR PR https://github.com/servo/webrender/pull/2693", "author": "lsalzman@mozilla.com", "id": 13234246, "time": "2018-04-26T02:06:46Z"}], "id": 1452563, "priority": "P1", "cc": ["a.beingessner@gmail.com", "bugmail@mozilla.staktrace.com", "jan@ikenmeyer.eu", "jmuizelaar@mozilla.com", "milaninbugzilla@gmail.com"], "cf_crash_signature": "", "version": "61 Bra